Place Name: A R AND F DITTERICH RESERVE
Historical Information:
Arthur Ralph Ditterich was a Shire of Flinders Councillor from 1961-1964.
A.R. & F. Ditterich are Life Members of the Main Ridge Cricket Club - Ralph and Frank Ditterich were keen cricketers and involved in community affairs. They were involved in the planning and building of the bowls club and other works associated with the grounds. Both had orchards and lived in Valley View Lane, Main Ridge.  Prior to 1926 Main Ridge was known as Main Creek and the name change was brought about by Frank Ditterich.  Seven acres (2.8 hectares) was bought from C. Rigby in 1932 for a recreation ground at Main Ridge for the sum of 50 pounds ($100). A 10 pound ($20) deposit was raised by the community funded in part by a 'sheep guessing competition'. The balance payable over 5 years was raised by community fundraising efforts.
In 1957 the gates were given as a gift by Mrs Lillian Adams of Main Ridge.
On 28th April 1959 the Shire President was invited to unveil a plaque in memory of Frank Ditterich.  Frank was born in Long Gully, Bendigo on 17th September 1895 and died on 28th December 1956 at Mentone. He married his wife Jessie in 1930. They had two sons Richard and David.
Ralph was born in St Arnaud on 4th July, 1893 and married his wife Margaret in Palmerston, New Zealand in 1926. Their son Allan was born in 1929 and died in 1947. Ralph died in Redcliffe, Queensland in 1974.
Councillor A. R. McNabb, Mayor of the City 1947-48.

It was listed among the civic assets by Cr F. Linley in his submission to the Railway Commissioners, noting then that money was being spent on football and cricket at the reserve. A further two acres (.8 hectare) were acquired there in 1948.

Historical Information: Arthur Calwell (1896-1973) was an Australia politician, serving on the City of Melbourne Council, and the House of Representatives as member for Melbourne. He served in the Curtin government as Minister for Information, and subsequently Minister for Immigration in the Chifley government. He was the architect and builder of the Australian immigration program after the Second World War. After the death of Chifley, he was appointed Deputy Leader, and Leader of the Opposition.

B.A. Cairns Reserve was developed in the 1880s as a sports venue for cricket and football, but was also used for gymkhanas and stock auctions.  In the 1970s it was named after Bertie Alexander Cairns (1895-1979), a member of the pioneering Cairns family, in acknowledgment of his tireless dedication to the care and maintenance of the sporting reserve.
Bert did so much valued service, especially for the Park and Cricket Club. He was also a very good golfer. As a General Carrier for many years, he transported fish and other produce to the markets and brought goods back for the farmers and residents.
He is buried with his wife in the Flinders Cemetery.
The name, meaning 'mother's foot', was bestowed by Wurundjeri elder, Doreen Wandin-Garvey, on 14 August 2006 in recognition of the cultural significance of the site.

A written submision was made to Council by Mr & Mrs Pedretti.

Mr Donald Baidwyn noted that the park area which was land deemed for recreational use when the developer was given permission to develop the Orchard Circuit/Dunstan Court Estate as part of the planning for that estate, was undeveloped. He called on local residents in the area for their support and organised contact with local councillors to meet with residents at a park BBQ held on the site, which was met with a very positive response. Mr Baldwyn had plans drawn up for submission to council for their approval. The plans were adapted for what the park is now. He collected donations from residents for the purchase of trees/shrubs for the area in addition to what council gave so that the area would be well covered around the outer boundaries. Once these trees were purchased, and the land semi developed by council, he organised a working bee for the planting of these trees and shrubs. He also developed a roster for the watering and care of these plants to assist in their early establishment. To this day, he still tends to the park, inspecting the plants for care and the grassed area to see if it needs watering. The park is much used by families as an area to fly kites, kick the footy, play soccer and football, and is also used by some elderly as a walking area, where they may take a seat when they tire, or to just watch the world go by in a peaceful environment, thanks to his foresight in developing this area.

Historical Information: Commemorates William Barak an elder and a great nineteenth centry leader of the Wurundjeri people.  He lived from 1824 to 1903, before the arrival of the white settlers through the establishment of Melbourne to Federation (1901).  Barak in his day was held in the highest esteem among his own people and wider white community.  Today's Wurundgeri Elders are descendents of the Barak line.
Namered after local resident Barbara Beyer who established the Seddon Croquet Club

Barbara Beyer was a founding member of the concept of the Footscray and District Hospital, was a founder and honorary Secretary of the Footscray Creche and Kindergarten for 27 years, and was the founder and President of the Seddon Croquet Club.

The Barbers were one of Somerville's early well-known nursery families.
In the mid-1800s, Claude Barber settled on a property in Lower Somerville Road. He then bought a 60-acre (24 hectare) property in Eramosa Road which was the first property on the Mornington Peninsula with the name of "Western Port". The original drive into the homestead was located in the area of today's Jordan Street. Barber Reserve is part of a former paddock on the farm property.  The orchard covered approximately 40 acres (16 hectares).

Community consultation to name the park occurred in 2014. The name Barclay was suggested by the Greensborough Historical Society as an option. Their records indicate that in the 1940's this part of Greensborough comprised 5 to 10 acre farmlets, one of which was home to the Barclay family. Henry Barwell Barclay, his wife Dorothy and their six month old son Eric moved to a 10 acre holding at Grace Park, at the end of Henry Street where it intersects with Elder Street, Greensborough in 1938. This farmlet stood where Gladman Street in now located (approximately 350 m south of McKenzie Court). Henry Barclay worked locally, in the market garden at nearby Yallambie House, a mansion on large acreage that fronted the Plenty River, and the produce merchant Stubley's in Greensborough, where he loaded wheat. Henry Barclay died in November 1959.

Bill Carroll spoke at the 1967 Annual General meeting of the Merricks Yacht Club, for the need of the young people of Merricks Beach to have a focal point in which to spend their evenings and leisure time, suggesting the need for a club house. Commodore Thiemeyer wrote to the Foreshore Committee and approval for the construction of a club house was given. A sum of $4,000 was raised and club house was commenced in November, 1968.

The Bill Carroll, or Palmers Hill Road Reserve is a small area of native vegetation at Merricks Beach. It was created in 1993 due to the interest of a group of Merricks Beach residents. A Committee of Management was formed to draw up a plan for submission to the Hastings Council and the area, which had formerly been grazing land, underwent a transformation to become a nature reserve.

Historical Information:
The first European tracks in this area linked the main pastoral properties, coming from Frankston via Carrup Carrup and Bunguyan to Coolart and also from Dandenong, via Bunguyan. A surveyor's map of 1858 shows "dray tracks" from both directions crossing at King's Bunguyan Cattle Station Pre-emptive Right, near the present site of Tyabb.
The Bunguyan or King's Cattle Station covered 15,000 acres (6.700 hectares) on the west side of Western Port when it was licensed to Martha Jane King in 1845.
Named after the 'Bunguyan' run held by Martha Jane King between 1845 - 59. 'Mrs. King was one of the very few women in this country to hold a run from original licence to land survey'.

Historical Information: 'This park overlooks a historic road intersection.  During the 19th century travellers to the northern goldfields often took the route up to Mt. Alexander Road, along the Bulla or Deep Creek Road (Now Melrose Drive), and turning right here down Broadmeadows Road (now Mickleham Road) to join what was the old Sydney Road.  The Junction Hotel, on the opposite north-western corner was a popular overnight stopover and this park would have seen many travellers tents.  By the start of the 20th century this park was part of the Camp Hill property owned by the Gilligan brothers.'

Carl Fietz and his wife, Anna, established a home in Leneva in 1879, with Carl working daily as a blacksmith in Wodonga. They went on to have 14 children and 40 grandchildren and were one of Wodonga's earliest pioneer families. Carl was from Germany and arrived on the ship Emmy.

Named after Caroline Chisholm (1808-1877). Caroline Chisholm worked tirelessly for female immigrants in NSW, as it was her belief that the best influences on colonial life were marriage and family life. She had continued this work on her return to England, and had encouraged poor people, especially young women, to leave the squalor of their homeland and emigrate to Australia. Her work in Victoria was in providing clean, cheap and safe accommodation to families or single people on the way to the Mount Alexander diggings. She pressured the government into a scheme to built ten shelter sheds, which would provide accommodation for single men, single women and families. While none of the sheds lasted, the park is in the rough area where the sheds were located.
Park takes its name from the estate named 'Castle Heights' by developers.

Historical Information: Named after 'Catjump Kindergarten' which takes its name from Catjump Road.' 'It is so named because of an earlier association in the formation years of the Kindergarten with a road named 'Catjump Road' although the Kindergarten and Catjump Road are now approximately 3/4 of a mile apart.' 'The origin of the name Catjump Road is said to have evolved from a conversation between Orchardists resident in Springvale Road beyond Catjump Road and a Councillor about the turn of the century.  The Orchardists were seeking a connecting road from Springvale Road and Old Warrandyte Road to Doncaster Road and one of them asked the Councillor whether the residents would be getting their new road and the Councillor, having in mind an even vote requiring a casting vote by the President replied 'It will depend on the way the cat jumps'.

Yarra Ranges National Park. Named after Cumberland Creek (2). Established 1923 (Forests Commission tourist reserve) and 1929; the word Memorial was added to the name in 1994. A memorial, suggested by nursing sisters Bolam and McGowan [Mary Kenealy], to Australians who died during the First and Second World Wars and later conflicts. Includes the Cambarville picnic area, the Cumberland walking track, the Cumberland and Corra Linn Falls, lookouts, The Big Culvert, an historic water-race, fine stands of mountain ash and myrtle beech, the Big Tree (83 m high Eucalyptus regnans), and a Sitka spruce (Picea sitchensis) marking the site of the home of George Loch, timber cutter and gold miner, who lived there until 1938. Leadbeater's possum was rediscovered in the area in 1961.
Author: Sinnott, Nigel

Historical Information: Named in recognition of Cyril Fox's outstanding efforts and active contribution to sport within the Crib Point community. He served in the Royal Australian Navy for 21 years, including war service in the Pacific. He was a member of the Crib Point Football Club, Tennis Club, and the Devilbend Golf Club, as well as serving on the Council as Shire President and a number of community committees.

Cyril Edward Fox (1921-2006) left school at the age of 14 years and worked at the Islington Railway Workshops until World War II broke out. He then joined the Australian Navy in April 1940.  In 1946 Cyril was drafted to the Flinders Naval Depot to do a physical training course after which he was sent to New
Guinea. When he returned he was appointed to the Naval College as a Physical Training Instructor.  He retired from the Navy in 1961 after completing 21 years of service.
Cyril commenced a new occupation with the Education Department of Victoria as Physical Education teacher at Aspendale Technical School. He also taught at Dromana and Frankston before retiring from teaching.
He was a Hastings Shire Councillor, representing Bittern, and a Shire President.
He was on the Crib Point Swimming Pool Advisory Committee in 1980-81, the Hastings Red Cross Committee, and the Crib Point Primary School Committee in 1981.  C.E. Fox was also a Justice of the Peace.
The Cyril Fox Bushland Reserve is a 2.3 hectare reserve of high quality remnant vegetation adjacent to the Cyril Fox Recreation Reserve.
Named after Cyril Ward, whose family has been continuously involved in the Hastings community since 1871, firstly as a fishing family and later as orchardists.

Historical Information: 'In 1837 Captain William Lonsdale chose a larger area than that referred to in the request as a station for a Native Police Corps.  Lonsdale referred to the location of the location of the station as 'on the Dangy-nong Creek at Nerre Nerre Warrene'.  Neither of these forms of spelling survived.  The Native Police were disbanded in 1851 and the area was then used as a stun depot for Police horses.  The depot acquired its first horses in 1856.'  'Available evidence suggests that the name 'Dandenong Police Paddocks' gradually superseded the older locality name 'Nerre Nerre Warrene' after the establishment of the stud depot.'

Historical Information: On Friday 7 December, 1951, a 49-year-old housewife named Mrs. Elsie Dorrington became the Shire of Mornington's first woman Councillor, when six hundred ratepayers decided to break with tradition of no women in the Shire Council. Cr. Dorringtons' first job was to urge the Council to set up a home-help scheme and she also went on to initiate a number of social welfare schemes in the Shire. Mrs Dorrington served three terms as Councillor until 1958. In 1960 Mrs Dorrington was appointed as Victorian Justice of the Peace and sat on the bench at Mornington's Magistrates Court. From 1961 to 1969, Mrs Dorrington worked for the Department of Mental Hygiene as the Manager of Moorakyne Girls Hostel in Hawthorn. Elsie Dorrington passed away on 1 June, 1995 in Mount Eliza.

Historical Information: Originally called Burial Hill, this rise at the western end of the city grid was renamed when the flagstaff was erected in September 1840 for signalling shipping activities in Hobsons Bay. George Gordon McCrae reminisced that 'Bunting and great wicker balls' told what type of vessel was approaching and the port of origin. Marryat's code of signal flags was used to carry news from Williamstown. The advent of the telegraph rendered the flagstaff redundant and operation ceased on 1 October 1857. The signaller's store and dwelling were incorporated into the Flagstaff Observatory. At 130 ft (39.6 m) in height, and with better sight lines of Williams-town and the bay, Flagstaff Hill had been preferred to Batmans Hill as the observatory site. The Flagstaff Gardens were planted on the site in the 1860s.
Author: Judy Macdonald

Historical Information: Flagstaff Gardens is the oldest park in Melbourne, Victoria, Australia, first established in 1862. In 2005 it is one of the most visited and widely used parks in the city by nearby office workers and tourists. The gardens are notable for their archaeological, horticultural, historical and social significance to the history of Melbourne. The gardens are 7.2 hectares (18 acres) of Crown Land bounded by William, La Trobe, King and Dudley streets, managed by the City of Melbourne. On the south-east corner opposite is the entrance to Flagstaff railway station. Diagonally opposite stands the Victorian branch of the Royal Mint, established 7 August 1869. The former Royal Mint building is a well-preserved example of Victorian Gold Rush boom-period classical styled architecture. The facade features paired columns with scrolled capitals and the Royal Mint coat-of-arms. On the northeast corner over William Street, is the Queen Victoria Market. The park contains extensive lawns with a variety of mature trees, flowerbeds and wild animals including possums. The southern end is characterised by deciduous trees, while the northern end contains mature eucalypts. Avenues of elms shade pathways along with several large Moreton Bay Fig trees. The north corner contains a bowling lawn, rose beds, flower and shrub beds. Along William Street there are tennis courts, which also double as volleyball, handball and netball courts. Electric barbecues nearby provides a popular site for office parties in December. Scattered about the lawns and gardens are memorials and sculptures that illuminate some of the social significance of the area. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flagstaff_Gardens

Harold Caterson was a member of Moorabbin Rugby Union Football Club's first committee, he was at the initial meeting in December 1964 that agreed to create a rugby club in Moorabbin to commence in season 1965. He was a long-term committee member (in various positions) and club member in the 60s, 70s and 80s and he was key in establishing a home for Moorabbin at Keys. Rd. Additionally, he was involved on the Management Committee of the Victorian Rugby Union over many years.
In the history of the club Harold Caterson and Jack McDavitt stand out as the two most influential club members who founded, developed and built Moorabbin Rugby Club from scratch.
Jack has, appropriately, had the extended clubrooms (originally built in 1978) named in his honour for his contribution to the club. The reserve was renamed in honour of Harold's contribution to the club.

Keys Rd ground was an old rubbish tip that had been filled and covered in a layer of soil. The surface was continually subsiding, in 1965 junior cricket was played on this ground and the oval was found unsuitable for cricket; it was actually a muddy paddock in winter and a corrugated concrete oval in summer. Cricket never returned to this oval.
Harold could see the potential in the Keys Rd Reserve and in 1967 donated the cost of a single car steel garage placed on a concrete slab, which was to become our first changing room/clubroom, and was later known as "the old tin shed". It had the nickname of "Mr. Cat's Cottage" on a sign above the door.
The following year a small extension was added that held a briquette hot water service and several showers.
As the Club grew over the years, Harold continued to be a committee member and also continued to liaise with Council regarding club matters. Whether it was gaining approval for further extensions to the shed (there were several extensions over the years), ground improvements, a second playing field, flood lighting and eventually Clubrooms were built in 1978.
Harold was the "go to person" in regard to Council. He developed a very good relationship with Mayor Bricker, who later became our Patron for many years and over time became one of the Rams strongest supporters.
Gaining significant funding for a sport that was practically unknown in the district, was not easy. The relationship between Harold and Cr. Bricker proved vital on several occasions as the councillor supported funding for the club which otherwise might not have been approved.
That the Rams are based at Keys Road can be put down to Harold's dedication to securing a permanent home for rugby union in Moorabbin.

The club's playing jersey is also a legacy from Harold Caterson's U18 Marlins team.
He was President in 1968 and 1971; Vice President in 1969, 1970 and from 1972 to 1981 inclusive. Ordinary Committee Member 1965 to 1967.
Harold was made a Life Member in 1977.
Additionally, he was the Moorabbin club delegate to the Victorian Rugby Union for many years; and he would collate the results and statistics for the VRU weekly magazine each week during the season.
His work with the club, Council and the VRU continued right up to his sudden death in 1981.
It is worth noting that four generations of the Caterson family have been involved in playing and administrating the Moorabbin Rugby Club since its inception in 1965.
Author: Ian Ray
Title: Life Member Moorabbin Rugby Club

''The Hayes Reserve' after early pioneers of this area.  Mark Hayes selected the land at Tooborac in August 1857 and the family lived in tenets on a little creek on the east side of the road (which is now the reserve in question) until the stone house 'Leicester House' was built.  This was finished and occupied by 1862.  The House was continuously lived in by members of the Hayes family, until the property was sold in the 1970's.  The ship Mark and his family arrived in Australia aboard was the 'Harry Lorrequest', which sailed from Plymouth 27th November, 1850.  It arrived in Port Phillip on 14th March, 1851.'

Historical Information: 'The Hazelwood station was named after Mrs Hazel Bennett wife of William Bennett, and sister of Albert Eugene Brodribb, who were co-holders of the station from 1844 to 1852.  The Bennetts held it alone from 1852 - 60.  Mrs Bennett was the first white woman to live in the Morwell area.  The Bennett family played an important part in the early development of Gippsland.  The Revd. Francis Hales in his Diary, kept during his pioneering ministerial journey through Gippsland in 1848, states that he stayed a night at 'the comfortable Bennett home at Hazelwood.'  Bishop Perry and Mrs Perry called there in 1849.'

Historical Information:
WURRUMBIT BIRRNG YAAR
Meaning: Long waterhole in the Merri River at Woodford.
Source: Dawson 1881
Pronunciation: WOO-ROOM-BIT BEER-NG YAR

It is clear from historical records the original local Aboriginal name for the site now known as Jubilee Park was as indicated above. It is normally the case with places of importance to Aboriginal people that several names are evident and are in close proximity to each other.  This demonstrates the local clan/s particular relationship with each site.
Author: Dawson, James
Title: Australian Aborigines

Historical Information: Annie Greenaway (1874-1953) was one of the earliest settlers of Hiawatha, settling in the area with her husband in 1910. Historical Information: 'Moondarra run was taken up in the early 1850's by Henry Dutton and David Okeden.  It later changed hands twice before being cancelled in 1861.  Moondarra township was gazetted in 1891 and surveyed in 1899.  A Survey plan was published in 1917.  Successive revocations of the township led to its extinction by 1952.  It is understood that the name is Aboriginal, Mundara meaning 'plenty of rain' or 'thunder'.'

The council purchased Alexandra Park for Â£200 ($400) in 1896. This became the Mornington Football Club's home ground, and it is now home to Mornington Football Netball & Cricket Clubs. The Mornington Cricket Club was established in 1863.  By 1905 the reserve was fenced and charges were made for entry, half the proceeds going towards improvements.  It was listed among the civic assets by Cr F. Linley in his submission to the Railway Commissioners, noting then that money was being spent on football and cricket at the reserve. A further two acres (.8 hectare) were acquired there in 1948. 
Possibly named in honour of Queen Alexandra, mother of King George V who reigned between 1910-1936, and after who King Georges Ave in Mornington was named.

A submission was received by the Nillumbik Shire Council on 6 June 2011 from the Strathewen Recreation Reserve Association and the Strathewen Cricket Club requesting that the newly built Strathewen Pavilion, located at the Strathewen Recreation Reserve be formally named the Peter Avola Memorial Pavilion.

Peter Avola lived in Strathewen for 39 years and perished in the Victorian Bushfires of 2009 at the Recreation Reserve. Peter was heavily involved with getting the reserve set up in the early 1980's and, from then on, Peter took on the job of maintaining the oval and surrounding areas. He did this on a voluntary basis for nearly 30 years using his own time, machinery and fuel.

Council, at its 27 March 2012 meeting, resolved that it approve the naming of the Strathewen Pavilion as the Peter Avola Memorial Pavilion.

Following approval of the name by the Registrar of Geographic Names, notice of the registration of the name was published in the Victoria Government Gazette on 17 May 2012 with a subsequent Notice of Corrigendum published on 24 May 2012.

Historical Information: 'The Franke family moved to Smiths Gully in 1959 and owned land adjoining the Smiths Gully Picnic and Nature Reserve.  Smiths Gully was then quite a remote area with no electricity, very rough roads and acres of virgin bush.  Peter was the second of four children and as children the Frankes traveled extensively by foot and bicycle spending much time playing along the creek, around the mines, the crusher (burnt out in 1962) and the dam which form part of the Smiths Gully Picnic and Nature Reserve.'  'Peter Franke died on the 21st June, 1975, aged 20.  At the time of his death Peter was in his final year at Melbourne University doing veterinary science.  His sudden death was felt both by his family and the local community and the sympathy, consolation and thought from friends led to the suggestion of the naming of the reserve in memory of Peter.'
Author: Place Names Committee Files
Title: Submission

Historical Information:
Ralph Goode enlisted on 16 August 1914, the first man from Lilydale to do so. He was allotted to the 2nd Field Ambulance to serve as a stretcher bearer and he travelled on the SS Wiltshire in the first convoy to Egypt. He was stationed there until he moved to Lemnos Island and then was at the landing at Gallipoli. He saw service at Anzac Cove and Cape Helles and was there at the Battle of Lone Pine. He was Mentioned in Despatches for his work here. After the evacuation, he was sent back to Egypt where his unit was re-organised and then moved to France.
Between 1916 and 1918 he served on the Western Front, experiencing all the horrors and heroism of those campaigns. He was a veteran of Pozieres, Bullecourt, Passchendaele, Ypres and Delville Wood. In 1918 he returned home to Lilydale, married, had a family and took up a business running a drapers store in Lilydale's Main Street. He also did community work and achieved an extraordinary amount for that township. His family believed his way of coping with what he saw during the war years was to keep himself busy with community work. He was awarded the MBE for his efforts for that community. He died in 1961.
Author: Anthony McAleer
Title: A Stretcher Bearer's War: the story of Ralph Goode MBE

Kulin name: Quor-nÃ¿Â³ng. Meaning not recorded. 

This name was recorded by A. W. Howitt, anthropologist, from conversations from sometime between 1897 and 1901 with William Barak, ngurungaeta (leader) of the Wurundjeri-willam, the traditional owners of what is now northern Melbourne, and Dick Richards, Barak's fellow Kulin countryman. The Kulin was an alliance of Aboriginal nations in central Victoria. Howitt jotted down Aboriginal names, mostly in the Woiwurrung language once spoken in the Melbourne area, corresponding to landmarks and municipalities that arose in Melbourne town during Barak's lifetime (c.1824 to 1903).
Author: Jason Gibson, Helen Gardner, Stephen Morey
Page Title: Rediscovered: the Aboriginal names for ten Melbourne suburbs

Historical Information: 'The name was given to the lake because of its unusual depth amongst Mallee lakes.  Tradition relates that a 'Dago bullocky,' riding in search of his team came upon this strange sheet of water, and expecting it to be, as usual in such swamps, a foot or so in depth, he boldly urged his horse across it.  A few steps, and the water was up to the saddle flaps, for the lake, though of the smallest, is 13 feet deep.  Out he scrambled in great alarm and rode back to camp crying out he had found a lake deep as the sea - a Sea Lake.'

This reserve is named in honour of two of Dromana's pioneering families: the Shaw family and the McKeown family.

The Shaw family (Benjamin and Elizabeth) arrived in Dromana in 1875 and established Kangerong Guest House. Their son Archibald Shaw married Maud McKeown, daughter of James and Catherine McKeown, and started the family connection. Archibald was elected President of the Flinders Shire Council in 1924. Archibald and Maud raised and educated five children in Dromana (Maurice, Ernest, Archibald, Elizabeth and John). Maurice was the long-term proprietor of the Shell Service Station in Dromana and Shaw's Motors on Nepean Highway for many years prior to his death in 1991 aged 87.

The McKeown family (James and Catherine) arrived in Dromana in 1864. James cut timber for the Dromana pier in 1874 and in 1889 bought Gracefield and land to the East, where they planted an apple orchard. That land covered the area on which the reserve is now located. From 1889 to 1891 they were caretakers at Heronswood and in 1892 the McKeowns built Aringa Guest House (Cnr of Clarendon and Foote Streets Dromana) which was managed by their daughters for over 70 years until after the Second World War. James and Catherine raised 12 children (five sons and seven daughters); one daughter, Edith, the source for the naming of Edith Place, died in Dromana in 1987 aged 100. Two further generations of the Shaw and McKeown families have since lived in Dromana.

The surrounding land and the land on which the reserve is located was subdivided by the descendants of the pioneering Shaws and McKeowns in 1977 and the reserve was transferred to the Shire of Flinders (and since Mornington Peninsula Shire) for use as public open space.
Author: McLear, Colin
Title: A Dreamtime of Dromana
Publisher: Dromana and District Historical Society Inc

Nicknamed after Mr Baker who owned the land for many years prior to the Second World War and after. During the early part of the war, the land was used as an Army training Camp where soldiers assembled from all over Victoria. In 1943, American soldiers from the Pacific region used the land as a recreation camp. Towards the end of the Second World War the site was used as a P.O.W camp including Italian prisoners. The nickname 'Starlight' originated because of Mr Baker's tendency to roam the land at night. He may have used his property for hunting because in those days it was virgin bushland and very isolated.

(b) a house on the ridge and close to the park which burnt down many years ago bore the name 'Temple in the Wind'.

Historical Information: Previously called Checkingurk (or Tichingorouk) and settled by Captain James Reid in 1840, 'The Briars' had a long association with the Balcombe family.  The name was given to a number of Balcombe properties in Australia, all borrowing from a homestead in the hills above the Jamestown, capital of St Helena, an island in the Atlantic Ocean operated under charter by the East India Company.  The homestead garden included briar roses.  [See 'Balcombe Family and "The Briars" Park, Mt Martha, Victoria', and research papers held at 'The Briars'.

She returned to teach at Wodonga South Primary School and was a councillor for Bonegilla ward from 1985 to 1993.  She was Mayor of Wodonga in 1989 and was inaugural chairwoman of the Albury-Wodonga Regional Arts Board.

Historical Information: The park was created as part of the residential development on the former Haig Street Primary School site. The park is named in honour of Vin Heffernan OAM, Councilor - City Of Heidelberg (1966-1985) Mayor (1979-80), State Member for Ivanhoe (1985-1996) and Minister for Small Business and Youth Affairs (1992-1996). There is a strong local connection to Vin Heffernan in Heidelberg Heights with the former Haig Street Primary School library, which stood on the site, named in his honour.
Named in honour of a former Member for Ivanhoe and mayor and councillor for the then City of Heidelberg.

The park was formerly known as Vin Heffernan Reserve. It was renamed in 2016 in order to free up the name 'Vin Heffernan' for use in a more suitable location.
Community consultation to rename the reserve occurred in early 2016. The name Radio Park is in recognition of a radio relay tower which was formerly located near the site prior to its development.

W. Ison was an early pioneer who settled in Werribee in 1855 and who became a leading figure in the community until his death in 1923. He was born in England and emmigrated with his wife to Victoria. He was a member of the Mechanics Insitute and Library Committee responsible for the erection of that building and also served on the Committee of Management of the Wydnham Racecourse and Recreation Reserve.

Additional information can be found on Council's previous minutes: Council - Corporate Development 15 December 2009, pages 263 - 266

Walter Cottrell lived his whole life in Wodonga.  His main transport was his bicycle. He became a drover of sheep and cattle, then worked for Albert Schlink who owned the first store south of the railway line.  He cut wood for the quarry boilers during the construction of Hume Weir.  His last job was with the Army at Bandiana.  He was a champion shooter and a life member of the Wodonga Show Society.  He kept pigeons and was in demand all over Victoria as a show judge.
Park adjacent to Waminda Neighbourhood House,  'Waminda' reputedly means 'women's refuge'.

The name was made up and used by an early settler who took 'wannarkbeel' (reputedly an indigenous word for banksia and bluegum), deleted 'beel' and added 'laddin', which related to his place of origin in Scotland.
Ward Morrison served on Wodonga Council 1955-57 and was president when the offices in Woodland Grove were opened.  He worked tirelessly to promote the importance of local government.

Named as a tribute to the sacrifice of Australians who have suffered and died in wars.

Wattle Park is the only Australian example of a comprehensively developed pleasure park established, owned and operated by a transport authority with the dual aim of promoting its transport services and providing a recreational facility for the public. The layout of the park and its buildings and structures remain intact in their original 1920s form. The name and theme of the park reflect the strong national fervour of the early decades of the century - the wattle is Australia's national floral emblem. It has a historical association with two prominent Melbourne identities, Orland Fenwick, a former lord mayor and Eliza Welch, widow of the co-founder of the retailing firm Ball & Welch, before it was purchased by the Hawthorn Tramways Trust.
Author: Heritage Council Victoria

Historical Information: Named after the Wieland family.  Carl Ferdinand Wieland (1827-1902) was an immigrant from Prussia who arrived in 1872.  He established the first orchard in the district with his wife Caroline.  He named the settlement of Heathmont after the heath growing on the low hilly slopes.  His grandsons, Norman and Stanley helped construct Heathmont's first railway station which opened in 1926. Stanley and his wife Thelma had an orchard in the area 1930 to 1950.  The reserve was formerly their horse paddock and dam.
Wiggy Jackson came to Wodonga in about 1920.  He worked for various road gangs and later in Albury as a garbage contractor. His family has significant links with Wodonga.
Named after two early settler families on the Bellarine Peninsula, both with members active in the Portarlington community.
Commemorates the owner of the land a Sir William Angliss.

William Bardoel emigrated from Holland in 1953 as a watchmaker. After his arrival, he became involved in the building industry, and his Company was responsible for the development of aesthetic cluster housing estates in Chelsea, Cheltenham, and Dingley. He was a very active community member and played a significant role in the development of Dingley.
Named after the first school teacher of the school which stood on the reserve's site.

William Moulder established a saddlery business in 1871 and was a significant Wodonga landowner, including a property named Wodonga Creek. Mr Moulder served on the council and built the first Wodonga baths from a jetty and enclosed area off the lagoon known as Huon's Lake in Belvoir Park.
Named after William Moulder who set up a saddler business in 1871, owned nearby property and was a local councillor.
Named in honour of William Robert Lees who was involved in the campaigning for and creation of many parks and reserves in the Noble Park area of which he had a strong association.
''William Symons Park' in memory of Mr. William Symons, a Victoria Cross winner during World War 1 at Gallipoli.  He was a former resident of Brunswick'.

Title: Submission

Historical Information: Willow Park was the property established by Fred and Julianna Heckendorf in 1869. The name was derived after they planted several willow trees around their property. The property changed ownership many times until some of it was subdivided for housing and the remainder was transferred to the council for public parklands.
Commemorates the pioneering of the quarry by William Wilson.
Full name adopted to improve identity. [Previously known as 'Wilson Botanic Park'.]

'Wingan' is possibly derived from 'wing' meaning 'ear'.  [Note that Les Blake, Place Names of Victoria, Rigby, Melbourne, 1977, p.280, suggested derivation from 'wangan' meaning 'reed bed at river mouth' is not accepted.  Research by I.D. Clark and D.A. Cahir, University of Ballarat, 2005.]

Laurel Street was originally known as Woodbine Avenue during the 'Tent Town' days.  'Woodbine' referred to English migrants who smoked Woodbine tobacco.  Naming the small park nearby was seen as a way of keeping the history alive.

Historical Information: John Woodland was Wodonga's first shire president, serving from 1876 until 1877. 'Woodlands' was the informal name in use locally prior to gazettal.
This piece of land was originally part of the "Woodland Estate" and the original homestead (Woodlands Homestead) located in Doon Court, Briar Hill.
